{
  "texts": [
    "They reviewed and classified recent literature into five categories:(1) Assessing the performance and limitations of LLMs related to the generation of code as a solution to tasks [12,13,22], multiple-choice or exam questions [10,39,40].",
    "(2) Position papers, surveys or interviews addressing implications [5,6,26] for education (e.g., curricula, pedagogy, assessment, etc.).",
    "(3) Using LLMs to analyze students' solutions and provide feedback [3,21,31], or fix errors [2,36,46].",
    "(4) Using LLMs to create teaching material (e.g., programming exercises [9], multiple-choice questions [43]) or learning objectives [41].",
    "(5) Studying the interactions between programmers (including students) and LLMs w.r.t."
  ]
}